text: So one of the, this is an area I've studied a bit at the request of some of my clients. And one of the things I always found fascinating about the high yield bond timing type strategy was trying to figure out where exactly it was able to harvest its excess returns. So for example, you mentioned specifically the goal of trying to avoid those significant and prolonged drawdowns. I would sort of put that in the bucket of we're trying to avoid those periods of expanding credit spreads. But there's also the opportunity to reinvest at higher and contracting credit spreads, positive repricing that might be purely fundamental economic sentiment driven. And then there's even the opportunity to potentially harvest some excess carry in high yield versus sort of a corresponding treasury benchmark during calmer market environments. So when you think full cycle and you look at a product like this, how would you think about where the majority of the excess return? Return comes from? Is it from the capital preservation? Is it from that repricing shock? Or is it from that? Hey, there's some good cumulative bips we can earn along the way.
